The conversion equations from spherical to rectangular coordinates $(x, y, z)$ are somewhat unintuitive if one does this without paper and pencil or a calculator: $\ (\rho\cos\theta)(\sin\phi) = x, (\rho\sin\theta)(\sin\phi) = y, (\rho\cos\phi) = z.$ Two things are easy to see here: $\ (\rho\sin\phi)$ is the same for each coordinate; thus, if we multiply $x$ by $2,$ $2(\rho\sin\phi) = 2(\rho\cos\theta)(\sin\phi),$ $y$ must be multiplied by $2,$ so $2y=z.$
How can we simplify the Cartesian coordinates to a point in the octant $z>0?$ The first thing we realize is that cartesian coordinates in the first octant are always positive, so dividing each by the sign of its first term results in coordinates in the desired direction. Said another way, if $\rho > 0$ and $0<\theta \leq \pi,$ $0 \leq \phi \leq \pi,$ there are no negative signs in $\rho.$ Thus we simplify the polar coordinates $(\rho, \theta, 2 \phi)$ to $(\rho,\theta,\phi),$ and we can say that $$(\rho\cos\theta)(\sin(2\phi)) = x, (\rho\sin\theta)(\sin(2\phi)) = 2y, (\rho\cos(2\phi)) = z.$$
Since the scalar cosecants comprise the direction cosines, we use the vectors $\hat{\imath}, 2 \hat{\jmath}, 4 \hat{k}$ as a basis for rectangular coordinates: $\frac{\hat{\imath}}{\sqrt{17}}=\frac{\hat{\jmath}}{\frac{\sqrt{17}}{2}}=\frac{\hat{k}}{\sqrt{51}}.$ From here on, it is necessary to judge to ourselves whether the question is looking for a matrix, so first check whether the problem should be in radians or degrees if the variables are in degrees: $$\operatorname{rect}(2, -1, -2) = \begin{bmatrix}\frac{1}{\sqrt{17}} & \frac{2}{\sqrt{17}} & \frac{2}{\sqrt{51}} \\ \frac{2}{\sqrt{17}} & \frac{1}{\sqrt{17}} & \frac{4}{\sqrt{51}} \\ -2 \sqrt{51} & -4 \sqrt{51} & \sqrt{51} \end{bmatrix} \cdot \begin{bmatrix}2 \\ -1 \\ -2 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}-2 \sqrt{17} \\ 2 \sqrt{17} \\ -10 \sqrt{34} \end{bmatrix} = \text{(Hint: Don't forget divisions)}
. $$
