draw(a--b--c--d--cycle);
label("$A$", a, W); label("$B$", b, N); label("$C$", c, E); label("$D$", d, S);
[/asy]

solution:
We draw a horizontal line through $B$ (meeting the $y$-axis at $P$) and a vertical line through $C$ (meeting the $x$-axis at $Q$).  Suppose the point of intersection of these two lines is $R$. [asy]
// draw axis
real low = -1; real high = 6;
draw((low, 0)--(high, 0), Arrow); draw((0, low)--(0, high - 1.5), Arrow);
label("$x$", (high, 0), E); label("$y$", (0, high - 1.5), N);

// draw quadrilateral
pair a = (0, 1); pair b = (1, 3); pair c = (5, 2); pair d = (4, 0);
draw(a--b--c--d--cycle);
label("$A$", a, W); label("$B$", b, N); label("$C$", c, E); label("$D$", d, S);

// add extra points/lines
pair p = (0, b.y); pair q = (c.x, 0); pair r = p + q;
label("$P$", p, W); label("$Q$", q, S); label("$R$", r, NE);
draw(p--r--q);
[/asy] We know that $P$ has coordinates $(0,3)$ (since $B$ has $y$-coordinate 3) and $Q$ has coordinates $(5,0)$ (since $C$ has $x$-coordinate 5), so $R$ has coordinates $(5,3)$.

